  <title>Week 2 Activity</title>
  <subsection xml:id="radii-problems">
    <title>Radii of Convergence</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the radius of convergence of this power series.
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{x^n}{2n+1}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We use the limit form for calculating radius of convergence.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{c_n}{c_{n+1}} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{\frac{1}{2n+1}}{\frac{1}{2(n+1)+1}} 
              \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{(2n+3)}{(2n+1)} \right| = 1
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The radius of convergence is 1. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the radius of convergence of this power series.
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(x-3)^n}{n!(n+1)} 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We use the limit form for calculating radius of convergence.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{c_n}{c_{n+1}} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{\frac{1}{n!(n+1)}}{\frac{1}{(n+1)!(n+2)}} 
              \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{(n+1)!(n+2)}{n!(n+1)} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{(n+1)(n+2)}{(n+1)} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} n+2 = \infty 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The radius of convergence is <m>\infty</m>, meaning that the
          power series converges for all real numbers. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
