    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the radius of convergence of this power series.
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{n^2 x^n}{(n+3)!}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We use the limit form for calculating radius of convergence.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{c_n}{c_{n+1}} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{\frac{n^2}{(n+3)!}}{\frac{(n+1)^2}{(n+4)!}}
              \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{(n+4)! n^2}{(n+3)! (n+1)^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{(n+4)n^2}{(n+1)^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{n^3 + 4n^2}{n^2 + 2n + 1} = \infty
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The asymptotic order of the numerator is greater than the
          denominator, so the limit is <m>\infty</m>. The radius of
          convergence is <m>\infty</m>, which means that the power
          series converges for all real numbers. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
