  <subsection xml:id="taylor-series-problems">
    <title>Taylor Series</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the Taylor series for <m>f(x) = \ln x</m> centered
          at <m>\alpha = 3</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We follow the steps in the process. First, we find the
          first few derivatives of the function.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              f(x) = \ln x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime} (x) = \frac{1}{x} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime \prime} (x) = \frac{-1}{x^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime \prime \prime} (x) = \frac{2}{x^3} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{(4)} (x) = \frac{-6}{x^4} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{(5)} (x) = \frac{24}{x^5}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then we evaluate at the centre point.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              f(3) = \ln 3 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime} (3) = \frac{1}{3} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime \prime} (3) = \frac{-1}{3^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime \prime \prime} (3) = \frac{2}{3^3} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{(4)} (3) = \frac{-(2)(3)}{3^4} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{(5)} (3) = \frac{(2)(3)(4)}{3^5}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          We try to set a pattern for these derivatives evaluated at
          the centre point. We notice an alterning sign, which
          is represented by <m>(-1)^{n+1}</m>. We need the exponent
          <m>(n+1)</m> since the terms are even when the index is odd.
          Then the numerator is building up a factorial, stoping at
          one place less than the index: we can write this as
          <m>(n-1)!</m>. Finally, the denomniator is constructing a
          power of 3 with the exponent equal to the index. 
          <me>
            f^{(n)} (3) = \frac{(-1)^{n+1} (n-1)!}{3^n} 
          </me>
          Finally, we put this into the form of a taylor series. Here
          is the general form.
          <me>
            f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{f^{(n)}(\alpha)}{n!}
            (x-\alpha)^n
          </me>
          We put in the centre points and the pattern of our
          derivatives to determine the taylor series. However, the
          first term doens't fit the general pattern for this series,
          so we have to write the first term outside the <m>\Sigma</m>
          notation. 
          <me>
            f(x) = \ln 3 \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{n+1}
            (n-1)!}{3^n n!} (x-3)^n = \ln 3 + \sum_{n=1}^\infty
            \frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n3^n}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the Taylor series for <m>f(x) = sin x</m> centered
          at <m>\alpha = \frac{\pi}{2} </m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We follow the steps in the process. First, we find the
          first few derivatives of the function.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              f(x) = \sin x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime} (x) = \cos x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime \prime} (x) = -\sin x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime \prime \prime} (x) = -\cos x 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{(4)} (x) = \sin x
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{(5)} (x) = \cos x
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then we evaluate at the centre point.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              f\left( \frac{\pi}{2} \right) = 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime} \left( \frac{\pi}{2} \right) = 0
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime \prime} \left( \frac{\pi}{2} \right) = -1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime \prime \prime} \left( \frac{\pi}{2} \right) =
              0
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{(4)} \left( \frac{\pi}{2} \right) = 1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{(5)} \left( \frac{\pi}{2} \right) = 0
            </mrow>
          </md>
          We try to set a pattern for these derivatives evaluated at
          the centre point. We have an alternating patterns of zeros
          and positive/negative ones. Since all the odd terms are
          zeros, we can ignore the indices <m>(2n+1)</m> and just use
          the indices <m>(2n)</m>. Then when <m>n</m> in the
          <m>(2n)</m> is even, we have positive values, and when it is
          odd, we have negative values. Therefore, we can match indies
          <m>(2n)</m> with a derivative value of <m>(-1)^n</m>
          <md>
            <mrow>
            f^{(2n+1)} \left( \frac{\pi}{2} \right) = 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
            f^{(2n)} \left( \frac{\pi}{2} \right) = (-1)^n
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Finally, we put this into the form of a taylor series. Here
          is the general form.
          <me>
            f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{f^{(n)}(\alpha)}{n!}
            (x-\alpha)^n
          </me>
          We put in the centre points and the pattern of our
          derivatives to determine the taylor series. Since the odd
          indicies are zero, we simply won't include them in the sum. 
          <me>
            f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{(2n)!}
            \left(x - \frac{\pi}{2}\right)^{2n}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the Taylor series for <m>f(x) = x^4 + 7x^3 - 3x^2
          - 6x + 1</m> centered at <m>\alpha = 0</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This is a trick question. We could do all the steps above,
          and they would certainly work. We wouldn't get a patterns,
          but we would explicitly get the first five derivatives and
          all higher derivatives would be zero. We could put those
          derivatives into the form and calcluate the result. However,
          what we would get from that process would be exactly what we
          started with. 
        </p>
        <p>
          This makes an important point. A polynomial is already a
          taylor series (at least centred at zero). Since taylor
          series are unique
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
