  <subsection xml:id="approximation-problems">
    <title>Approximation</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the function <m>f(x) = \cos x</m> centred at
          <m>\alpha = 2\pi</m>. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              Inside the radius <m>4\pi</m>, what is the error of the
              35th order approximation?
            </li>
            <li>
              What radius is required for a 10th order approximation
              with error bounded by <m>10^{-6}</m>?
            </li>
            <li>
              Inside the radius <m>2\pi</m>, what order is needed for
              an error less than <m>10^{-1}</m>. 
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Inside the radius <m>4\pi</m>, what is the error of
                the 35th order approximation?
              </p>
              <p>
                The radius <m>d = 4\pi</m> and the order <m>n=36</m>
                are already given. To use the Lagrange error bound, I
                need to calculate <m>M</m>. Thankfully, the trig
                functions are easy to work with here: due to the cycle
                of derivatives, I can take <m>M=1</m> for any order.
                I'll move on by writing the Lagrange error bound.
                <me>
                  |R_{35}(x)| \leq \frac{M}{36!} |x-2\pi|^{36}
                </me>
                This still has <m>|x-2\pi|</m>, giving the error for
                specific points in the interval. The farther we can be
                from the centre point is the radius, so the largest
                possible value of <m>|x-2\pi|</m> is <m>d=4 \pi</m>.
                I'll make that replacement to get an error bound that
                applies to the whole interval.
                <me>
                  |R_{35}(x)| \leq \frac{1}{36!} (4\pi)^{36} \doteq 
                  0.01002
                </me>
                The error bound is just slightly larger than
                <m>\frac{1}{100}</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What radius is required for a 10th order approximation
                with error bounded by <m>10^{-6}</m>?
              </p>
              <p>
                As with the first part, I can set <m>M=1</m>. The
                order is give (<m>n=10</m>), but <m>d</m> is unknown.
                Let me start by writing the Lagrange error bound.
                <me>
                  |R_{10}(x)| \leq \frac{M}{11!} |x-2\pi|^{11}
                </me>
                The maximum value of <m>|x-2\pi|</m> is the distance
                <m>d</m> out from the centre point, so I can replace
                <m>|x - 2\pi</m> with <m>d</m> to get an error bound
                which applies to the whole interval.
                <me>
                |R_{10}(x)| \leq \frac{1}{11!} d^{11}
                </me>
                I want the error to be less that <m>10^{-6}</m>, so I
                need to solve this inequality. 
                <md>
                  <mrow>
                    \frac{1}{11!} d^{11} \amp \leq \frac{1}{1000000} 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    d^{11} \amp \leq \frac{11!}{1000000} 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    d \amp \leq \sqrt[11]{\frac{11!}{1000000}} \doteq
                    1.398
                  </mrow>
                </md>
                I conclude that a radius of approximately <m>1.398</m>
                is possible while the 10th order approximation has
                error less than <m>10^{-6}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Inside the radius <m>2\pi</m>, what order is needed
                for an error less than <m>10^{-1}</m>. 
              </p>
              <p>
                As with the first two parts, I can set <m>M=1</m>. I
                don't know the order <m>n</m>, but I do know
                <m>d=2\pi</m> and that the error should be less than
                <m>10^{-1}</m>.  I'll start by writing the Lagrange
                error bound.
                <me>
                  |R_{n}(x)| \leq \frac{M}{(n+1)!} |x-2\pi|^{n+1}
                </me>
                The maximum value of <m>|x-2\pi|</m> is the radius,
                which is <m>2\pi</m>. I can make that replacement to
                get an error bound for the whole interval.
                <me>
                |R_{n}(x)| \leq \frac{1}{(n+1)!} (2\pi)^{n+1}
                </me>
                I want this error to be less that <m>\frac{1}{10}</m>,
                so I need to solve this inequality.
                <me>
                \frac{(2\pi)^{n+1}}{(n+1)!} \leq \frac{1}{10}
                </me>
                Solving this directly is very difficult due to the
                factorial term: I don't have algebraic techniques than
                can deal with the factorial along with the <m>n</m> in
                the exponent. However, since I know <m>n</m> must be a
                positive integer, I can guess until we find an order
                that works. I'll put approximate values in the order
                column in this table. 
                <md>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp \text{Order} \amp \amp \text{Error Bound} 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp n=4 \amp \amp |R_5(x)| \leq 85.5 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp n=9 \amp \amp |R_{10}(x)| \leq 26.4 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp n=14 \amp \amp |R_{15}(x)| \leq 0.718 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp n=15 \amp \amp |R_{16}(x)| \leq 0.282 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp n=16 \amp \amp |R_{17}(x)| \leq 0.104 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \amp n=17 \amp \amp |R_{18}(x)| \leq 0.0363
                  </mrow>
                </md>
              The 17th order is the first order which has error less
              than <m>\frac{1}{10}</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the function <m>f(x) = \ln x</m> centered at
          <m>\alpha = 1</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              Inside the radius <m>\frac{1}{4} </m>, what is the error
              of the 10th order approximation?
            </li>
            <li>
              What radius is required for a 8th order approximation
              with error bounded by <m>10^{-3}</m>?
            </li>
            <li>
              Inside the radius <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, what order is
              needed for an error less than <m>10^{-2}</m>. 
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Inside the radius <m>\frac{1}{4} </m>, what is the
                error of the 10th order approximation?
              </p>
              <p>
              The radius <m>d = \frac{1}{4}</m> and the order
              <m>n=10</m> are given. To use the Lagrange error bound,
              I also need the bound of the eleventh derivative. There
              is a nice pattern of derivatives for <m>\ln x</m>, which
              I used for calculating Taylor series in previous
              activities. The eleventh derivative is 
              <me>
                \frac{d^{11}}{dx^{11}} \ln x = \frac{10!}{x^{11}}
              </me>
              I am looking at the interval <m>\left( \frac{3}{4},
              \frac{5}{4} \right)</m>. This derivative is a decreasing
              function on this interval, so it has its maximum at the
              lowest point.  I evaluate the eleventh derivative at
              <m>x = \frac{3}{4}</m> to get <m>M</m>.
              <me>
                M = \frac{d^{11}}{dx^{11}} \ln x \Big|_{x=\frac{3}{4}} =
                \frac{10!}{\left( \frac{3}{4} \right)^{11}} =
                \frac{(4^{11})(10!)}{3^{11}} 
              </me>
              Then I put <m>M</m>, <m>d</m> and <m>n</m> into the
              Lagrange error bound.
              <me>
                |R_{10}(x)| \leq \frac{M}{11!} |x-1|^{11}
                = \frac{(4^{11})(10!)}{(3^{11})(11!)} |x-1|^{11}
                = \frac{4^{11}}{(3^{11})(11)} |x-1|^{11}
              </me>
              Finally, the largest value of <m>|x-1|</m> on the
              interval in equation is the radius <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>. I
              can replace <m>|x-1|</m> with this radius for a bound
              that applies to the whole interval.
              <me>
                |R_{10}(x)| \leq \frac{4^{11}}{(3^{11}(11)}
                \frac{1}{4^{11}} = \frac{1}{(3^{11}){11}} =
                \frac{1}{1948617} \doteq 0.000000513
              </me>
              The error of the 10th order approximation is less than
              <m>0.0000005</m>.
            </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                What radius is required for a 8th order approximation
                with error bounded by <m>10^{-3}</m>?
              </p>
              <p>
                To use Lagrange error bound, we first need <m>M</m>.
                Using the same logic as the first part, the 9th
                derivative is
                <me>
                  \frac{d^{9}}{dx^{9}} \ln x = \frac{8!}{x^{9}}
                </me>
                This is a decreasing function, so <m>M</m> is
                maximized at the smallest point on the interval. Since
                we're trying to find an unknown radius <m>d</m>, the
                smallest point on the interval is unknown and must
                simply be written. 
                <m>1-d</m>.
                <me>
                  M = \frac{d^{9}}{dx^{9}} \ln x \Big|_{x=(1-d)} =
                  \frac{8!}{(1-d)^9}
                </me>
                I can put this in the Lagrange error bound with
                <m>n=8</m>.
                <me>
                  |R_{8}(x)| \leq \frac{M}{9!} |x-1|^{9}
                  = \frac{1}{9 (1-d)^9} |x-1|^9
                </me>
                The maximum value of <m>|x-1|</m> will be at the
                futherest point in the interval. This distance is
                simply the radius <m>d</m> that I am looking for. 
                <me>
                |R_{8}(x)| \leq \frac{1}{9 (1-d)^9} d^9
                </me>
                So I need a radius <m>d</m> such that
                <m>\frac{d^9}{9(1-d)^9} \leq \frac{1}{1000}</m>. I can
                solve this inequality. (I will assume <m>d \in
                (0,1)</m>, so that multiplication by <m>(1-d)</m>
                preserves the inequality.) 
                <md>
                  <mrow>
                    \frac{d^9}{9(1-d)^9} \amp \leq \frac{1}{1000} 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \frac{1000}{9} \amp \leq \left(\frac{1-d}{d}
                    \right)^9 = \left( \frac{1}{d} - 1 \right)^9 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \sqrt[9]{\frac{1000}{9}} \amp \leq \frac{1}{d} - 1
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \sqrt[9]{\frac{1000}{9}} + 1 \amp \leq \frac{1}{d} 
                  </mrow>
                  <mrow>
                    \frac{1}{\sqrt[9]{\frac{1000}{9}} + 1} \amp \geq d 
                  </mrow>
                </md>
                If I approximate the left side, I get <m>d \lt
                0.372</m>.  This is the size of the interval that fits
                the desire order and error bound.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
              Inside the radius <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, what order is
              needed for an error less than <m>10^{-2}</m>. 
              </p>
              <p>
                I know <m>d</m> and the desired error, but <m>n</m> is
                unknown.  I have to use the general expression for the
                <m>n</m>th derivative.
                <me>
                  \frac{d^n}{dx^n} \ln x = \frac{(-1)^{n-1}(n-1)!}{x^n}
                </me>
                <m>M</m> is the bound on the <m>(n+1)</m>st derivative
                on the interval.  The derivative is always increasing,
                so the derivative is largest at <m>x= \frac{1}{2}</m>.
                <me>
                  M = \left| \frac{d^{n+1}}{dx^{n+1}} \ln x
                  \Big|_{x=\frac{1}{2}} \right| =
                  \frac{n!}{(\frac{1}{2})^{n+1}} = 2^{n+1} n! 
                </me>
                I put this in the error bound. The maximum value of
                <m>|x-1|</m> on the interval is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                <me>
                  |R_n(x)| \leq \frac{M}{(n+1)!} |x-1|^{n+1} \leq
                  \frac{2^{n+1} n!}{(n+1)!} \left( \frac{1}{2}
                  \right)^{n+1} = \frac{1}{n+1}
                </me>
                I need to choose <m>n</m> such that <m>\frac{1}{n+1}
                \leq \frac{1}{100}</m>, so <m>n+1 \geq 100</m>, which
                is <m>n \geq 99</m>. I need at least the 99th order
                approximation.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
